The Macedonian people voted to change the country's name.
The Macedonian people held a referendum on Sunday to determine the change of name to the ‘Republic of North Macedonia'. An act that would resolve a decade-long dispute with Greece in which Greece has prevented Macedonia from joining the European Union (EU) and the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
Greece, which has its own territory called Macedonia, insists that the name ‘Macedonia' represents a claim to its territory and has vetoed to reject Macedonia's participation in NATO and the EU.
The two governments reached an agreement on a proposed change of name in June but nationalist opposition said the change undermined the identity of the predominantly Slavic ethnic Macedonians.
President Gjorge Ivanov said he would not vote in the referendum and the vote cast doubt on whether the referendum would reach the minimum 50 per cent vote required for the referendum to be valid.
The question on the ballot was written: "Do you agree to join NATO and the EU with the acceptance of an agreement with Greece?"
Proponents of the name change include Prime Minister Zoran Zaev saying "The acceptance of the new name is a price worth paying to join the EU and NATO for Macedonia, one of the countries that emerged after the fall of Yugoslavia.
"I came today to vote for the future of the country and for the young people in Macedonia so that they can live freely under the European Union because that means our lives are safer," said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
Despite being illegal, lawmakers said they would abide by the vote's decision to make it final.
The change of name requires a two-thirds majority in parliament.
The country's electoral commission said there were no reports of non-ruled matters happening as of 1pm.
However, voter turnout was 16 per cent compared to 34 per cent in parliamentary elections in 2016 after 66 per cent of registered voters cast ballot papers.
"I came to vote because of my children. Our place in Europe," said Gjose Tanevski, 62, a voter in the capital Skopje.
Macedonian PM Zoran Zaev, his wife and their son Dushko cast ballot papers in Macedonia for the country's name change that would pave the way for Macedonia to join NATO and the EU in Strumica, Macedonia on September 30, 2018.
In front of the parliament in Skopje, 54-year-old Vladimir Kavardarkov was setting up a small stage and placing chairs in front of the tent set up by those who boycotted the referendum.
"We want to join NATO and the EU but we want to join it with pride and not this way," Kavadarkov said.
"We are poor people, but we have dignity.
If they don't want to see us as Macedonians, we can turn to China and Russia and become part of the Euro-Asian integration."
Prime Minister Zaev said participation in NATO would provide sufficient investment to Macedonia, where the unemployment rate is above 20 percent.
I believe a large majority will accept because more than 80 per cent of our population voted for the EU and NATO," Zaev said after voting.
He said the ‘yes’ decision was a ‘confirmation of our future.'
A poll was published on Monday by the Macedonian Institute for Policy Studies which said between 30 and 43 percent of voters would participate in the referendum - below the required amount.
Another poll, conducted by Macedonian TV Telma, found that as many as 57 percent of respondents planned to vote on Sunday.
Of those, 70 percent said they would vote yes.
For a vote to be successful the number of voters coming in must be 50 per cent plus one vote.
