John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Scottish private schools maintain a track record for academic excellence, and this has continued in 2018 with another set of excellent examination results, reinforced by individuals and collective success in sports, art, music and other community endeavors.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, the school, represented by the Scottish Board of Private Schools (SCIS), strives to serve at the best level to their students and parents.
The goal of private schools is to prepare their students to pursue higher education, their chosen career, and their place as global citizens.
As an education sector that they can and implement an earlier school curriculum, we see the modern language continues to be well-known and the subject of choice required within the school.
Nelson Mandela said: "If you talk to someone in a language that is understood, it will go into his head.
If you speak to him in his mother tongue, it will come into his heart."
This is a powerful reminder that we can't just rely on English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year's exam results, we can see that language is the top subject in the league table with the highest pass rates in private schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who learn a foreign language get a higher grade A.
This data, collected from 74 SCIS school members, showed 72 percent of students got a higher grade A in Mandarin, while 72 percent of them studied German, 69 percent of them learned French and 63 percent studied Spanish also got an A.
This shows that private schools in Scotland support foreign language as an important skill that children and young people will no doubt need it in the future.
The current language, as an optional subject, is being held just as is the subject of STEM (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curriculum of private schools and elsewhere.
A survey by the UK's Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found employers' reasons for struggling to meet the vacuum, 17 percent linked to language skills shortages.
Because of that over and over again, language skills have become a must to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more prospective employment opportunities requiring language, these skills are essential in this global world.
Regardless of a person's chosen career, if they learn a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future by having this kind of lifelong skill.
Being able to communicate directly with people from a foreign country will put someone who controls many languages automatically ahead of the competition.
According to YouGov's poll of more than 4,000 UK adults in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough for a conversation, with French as a conversational language used only by double-digit percentages, 15 percent.
This is why investing in language teaching is important for today's children.
Having multiple languages, especially the country is developing its economy, will equip children with better opportunities in finding meaningful jobs.
In Scotland, every school will be different in the language they learn.
Some schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach a language that is seen as crucial for the UK when it comes to looking ahead in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child is interested in, there are often many languages to choose from in private schools, with an instructor who specializes in the department.
Scottish private schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills necessary to succeed, no matter what happens in the future.
It is undeniable at this time, in a global business environment, that language continues to be very important to the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern language should be considered an ‘international communication skill.'
Private schools will continue to offer this option, diversity and excellence for young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is Director of the Council of Scottish Private Schools
