Harvard students have taken courses to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has given all of its students more sleep in an effort to combat a culture of learning that is becoming more and more so through 'overnight' based on caffeine.
A teaching staff finds students at the world's number one university often can't understand the basics of taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and an expert at Brigham and Women's Hospital, prepared a course he believed was the first of its kind in the United States.
He gained the inspiration to start the course after giving a talk about the effects of sleep deprivation during learning.
‘At the end of the course, a girl came to me and said: ‘Why am I only told about this now, in my senior year?’
He said no one had ever told him about the importance of sleep - and that surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course was introduced for the first time this year, explaining to students the need for good sleep habits to help academic performance and exercise, as well as improving their well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after finding its students were sleep deprived throughout the week.
The one-hour course involves several interactive assignments.
In one part, there is an image of a dormitory room, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, coaches and books to be informed about the effects of caffeine and light and how sports performance is affected by lack of sleep, and the importance of sleep routines.
In other sections, participants were told how long-term sleep deprivation could increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons, then encourage participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know it's not going to change the behavior of students right away.
But we believe they have the right to know - just as you have the right to know the health consequences when choosing to smoke," added Prof. Czeisler.
The culture of pride in ‘staying up all night' still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing stress on students mean sleep deprivation is an increasingly tapering problem.
Ensuring you have enough quality sleep, it should be a student's 'secret weapon' to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he says - even to avoid weight gain, because lack of sleep puts the brain into starvation mode, making it constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student studying chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, having taken his class last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to develop the course across campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all postgraduate students to complete the same learning program before joining a competitive institution.
Prof Czeisler suggests that students should consider the use of alarm clocks before and even after sleep, and be aware of the harmful effects of 'blue light' emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can damage your circadian rhythms from moving, causing sleep problems.
